MissionCommands.Message: {{capsuleName}}, this is mission control. Prepare the cockpit for launch.
Roger.
All right {{profileName}}, this is the real deal. Let's get this spacecraft ready for launch.
Roger.
We will go through the launch preparation checklist. I will set the switches on my side, and you will focus on those on your side. I will guide us through so follow my lead.
Roger.
You can access the Mission Pad to read about the mission by pressing [M] on the keyboard. I will give you 30 seconds to go through the details and briefing, also check out the PRE-LAUNCH checklist.
Roger.
Let's start with the Electrical Power System, following the PRE-FLIGHT checklist.
MAIN BATTERY 1 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 2 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 3 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 4 to ON.
Squib Battery 1 to ON.
Squib Battery 2 to ON.
Squib Battery 3 to ON.
Then the Fuel Cells on the main pilots panel. Set Fuel Cell stack 1A to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 1B to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 1C to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2A to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2B to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2C to ON.
Then set the Fuel Cell 1 Power to ON.
And Fuel Cell 2 Power to ON.
Set the Computer Power to ON.
Set the MDIU (Computer Display and Keyboard) to ON. The computer will run through some self-checks, this usually takes 20 seconds.
When the self-checks are complete (registers on the MDIU has stopped), start the computer by pressing START.
I will do my side. Arming BOOST-INSERT squibs.
Arming Retro Rocket 1
Arming Retro Rocket 2
Arming Retro Rocket 3
Arming Retro Rocket 4
Ok, electrical system and squibs are now set up. The last part of the checklist is mostly around the Environmental Control System.
We are going to use the built-in checklist feature to perform the last steps.
Open the [M]ission Pad again, go to Checklists, and find the PRE-FLIGHT checklist.
Press RUN to let the checklist guidance system help you set the remaining switches. Look for the blue guidance square and set the remaining switches.
{{capsuleName}}, all systems reading OK. We are go for launch.
Another feature of Reentry is timescaling. You can use the numeric keys to set the timescale. 1 is Normal time, and sequential numbers are multiplies of this.

Use the timescale to speed up time. The timescale will return to normal when a message is received, or before important stages. Timescale is blocked during powered maneuvers such as ascent and reentry etc.
Press 4 to speed up time.
{{capsuleName}}, 60 seconds to launch.
Roger.

{{profileName}}, use the [C]ommunications Menu to let ground know we are ready for launch. When the circular buttons are visible on the Commanders Seat, press the READY TO LAUNCH circular button, or else we won't go anywhere.
30 seconds to launch. It's good practice to briefly look over the major things to verify things are ready for launch.
Ok, this is it.
Good luck!
Lift off!
We are having a lot of vibrations. Systems looking good. Monitoring instruments. Over.
Roger. 30 seconds.
{{g}} g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage I fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go. Altitude increasing.
Roger. 60 seconds.
Staging feels good. Stage 2 ignited, red lights extuinguished. Stage 2 burning.
Roger.
{{g}}g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage II fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go.

Ok, we are now using Stage II to ascend into the initial orbit. This will mostly focus on building orbital speed as we power slightly above the horizon. User the VIEW SELECTOR to look outside when you have time.
Roger.
Such a beautiful view. Is this how you imagined Earth would look like from this altitude?
It's really beautiful.

One of the major differences between this spacecraft and those we flew in Project Mercury, is that it has the ability to maneuver and alter the orbit using translational thrusters. Also named the OAMS system.
Once Stage II is complete, we will use it to reach the exact planned orbit.
Enjoy the view, I will monitor the systems.
{{g}} g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage II fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go.
Roger. Prepare for SECO.
SECO!
Roger. Seperate from Stage II.
Roger. {{profileName}}, press the covered SEP SPCFT pushbutton to seperate us from the Launch Vehicle.
Separating from the Launch Vehicle.
Separation complete
Roger.
Next, remove the fairings with the button above to uncover our scanners, radar and sensors.

Please note that red SCANNER light on the center pedestal. If this is ON, the scanners are not able to track Earth. This is normal for about 120 seconds after jettisoning the fairings. Don't perform any automaneuvers if this light is on.
{{capsuleName}}, what is your IVI readings?
{{IVIs}}, will zero using OAMS.
Ok {{profileName}}, use the [M]ission Pad checklists to enable the OAMS system. This is the ENABLE OAMS checklist.
Then use the translational controls to zero the IVIs. It does not need to be exact for this mission, just give it your best shot.
The IVIs are seen on the Commanders side, so take a peek at them during the maneuver.
To modify the Orbit, you need to use the translational thrusters. Use [U] to go forward, [O] to backwards, [J] to go left, [L] to go right.
Give it your best shot while I prepare the stowage.
OK, this will do. Please execute the Orbit Insertion checklist to configure the cockpit to Orbit mode. Use the [M]ission Pad to RUN the INSERTION checklist.
Good. Feel free to look around and get familiar with the cockpit for a few minutes while I prepare the navigation.
{{capsuleName}}, we wish that you try the RATE COMMAND flight mode during the Orbit. Over.

Roger. {{profileName}}, use the RATE COMMAND MODE checklist to set the flight mode to manual rate command. In this mode, you can use [W] and [S] to pitch [A] and [D] to Yaw and [Q] and [E] to Roll. Give it a try!
We are about to reach the African coast and Madagascar, and we are about to transition into the night side of Earth. Check out the sunset by looking in the retrograde direction if you wish.

We are soon flying over Australia. The night lights from the major cities should easily be visible unless there are clouds. This also completes the mission. If you know the spacecraft, feel free to take it down through reentry! Good job today!

Title: The Titan
Description: The Gemini-Titan rocket is ready on the pad, where Commander Patrick and his crew will launch the first Gemini mission that will take the astronauts and the new spacecraft into an Orbit around Earth. One orbit is scheduled before returning back to Earth.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

The Gemini spacecraft will launch into Orbit using the Titan launch vehicle. The spacecraft will Orbit Earth once before firing the retrograde engines to return back to Earth and splash down in the Atlantic.

The retrograde sequence will start at 1 hour and 31 minutes into the flight, just when passing Texas. This will alter the orbital trajectory and reentry will happen just of the coast of Florida with a splashdown in the Atlantic Ocean.

The Mission will be completed when you are in Orbit. You can quit the mission here and the Commander will perform the reentry. If you know what you are doing, you can continue the mission and perform the reentry yourself.

Good luck!
